1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:08,325
(Luke 2:25): St Luke relates in his gospel that ‘when the days were accomplished Christ was brought to the temple.

2
00:00:08,325 --> 00:00:19,825
And behold there was a man in Jerusalem, Simeon by name, who was just and God-fearing, waiting for the consolation of the people of Israel and the Holy Ghost was in him.’

3
00:00:19,825 --> 00:00:20,887
‘And behold.’

4
00:00:20,887 --> 00:00:26,637
This particle et in Latin signifies joining, binding or locking together.

5
00:00:26,637 --> 00:00:30,850
Things fast bound or locked together are described as in union.

6
00:00:30,850 --> 00:00:35,437
Here I refer to the soul being bound, knit, united to God.

7
00:00:35,437 --> 00:00:39,125
According to our doctors, union postulates likeness.

8
00:00:39,125 --> 00:00:41,700
There is no union without likeness.

9
00:00:41,700 --> 00:00:45,687
Binding or knitting together, that is the meaning of union.

10
00:00:45,687 --> 00:00:52,812
Nearness to me does not constitute likeness: my sitting by someone or in the same place, for example.

11
00:00:52,812 --> 00:01:03,612
As St Augustine says, Lord, when I found myself afar from thee it was not from the remoteness of the place, it came of thy unlikeness wherein I found myself.

12
00:01:03,612 --> 00:01:10,187
One master says, people living and working wholly in time never agree, they never come together.

13
00:01:10,187 --> 00:01:19,075
According to our doctors, a thing whose life and work is in eternity and a thing whose life and work is here in time require a go-between.

14
00:01:19,075 --> 00:01:23,162
Where there is knitting and binding together there must be some likeness.

15
00:01:23,162 --> 00:01:27,212
The union of God and the soul is a matter of likeness.

16
00:01:27,212 --> 00:01:36,800
Where no difference exists there must be identity; not merely union in mutual embrace, but one; not merely likeness, but the same.

17
00:01:36,800 --> 00:01:43,600
Wherefore we say that the Son is not like the Father but he is his image, he is one with the Father.

18
00:01:43,600 --> 00:01:54,587
One of our best doctors says that an image in stone or on the wall, with no foundation to it, taken simply as a form, is the same form as his whose form it is.

19
00:01:54,587 --> 00:02:04,075
For the soul passing into her exemplar wherein is no alien thing, only her form wherewith it is one, this doctrine holds good.

20
00:02:04,075 --> 00:02:08,487
Having gotten the form that is divine we behold God, we find God.

21
00:02:08,487 --> 00:02:11,175
In separation God is not found.

22
00:02:11,175 --> 00:02:26,200
On passing into her exemplar and finding herself in that image alone, in that same image the soul finds God and the finding of herself and God, which is all the same act and is timeless, is the finding of God.

23
00:02:26,200 --> 00:02:30,000
So far as she is therein so far she is one with God.

24
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:35,475
He means: as far as a man is at the stage where his soul is the divine image.

25
00:02:35,475 --> 00:02:38,012
Then so far as he is he is divine.

26
00:02:38,012 --> 00:02:44,350
So far therein so far in God, not annexed, not united but one and the same.

27
00:02:44,450 --> 00:02:47,337
One master says, likeness means birth.

28
00:02:47,337 --> 00:02:52,462
Further he states that like is not met with in nature unless it is born.

29
00:02:52,462 --> 00:02:58,875
Doctors declare that fire, however fierce, would never burn had it no hope of propagation.

30
00:02:58,875 --> 00:03:05,287
However dry the wood supplied it would never catch (if fire) lacked power to generate its kind.

31
00:03:05,287 --> 00:03:11,025
What fire wants is to be born in wood, for all to be one fire, living and lasting.

32
00:03:11,025 --> 00:03:15,550
Extinguished and dead it were fire no more, so it wants to keep in.

33
00:03:15,550 --> 00:03:32,787
The nature of the soul would never have gotten its kind were it not for her wanting to have God begotten in her; she would not have proceeded into her nature, would never have wanted to enter therein, except in the hope of this birth; nor would God ever have brought it to pass had he not meant the soul to be born into him.

34
00:03:32,787 --> 00:03:35,562
God does and the soul desires.

35
00:03:35,562 --> 00:03:42,650
God has the energy and the soul has the will and the power to have God born into her and herself into God.

36
00:03:42,650 --> 00:03:46,800
This God contrives with intent that the soul shall be like him.

37
00:03:46,800 --> 00:03:55,250
She must needs wait for God to be gotten in her and for her treasure to grow into God, desiring union and the safekeeping of God.

38
00:03:55,250 --> 00:04:01,000
God’s nature pours into the light of the soul and therein she is preserved.

39
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:07,700
God purposes thus to be born into her, united with her, contained in her.—How can that be?

40
00:04:07,700 --> 00:04:17,362
Do we not say that God contains himself?—When he draws in the soul she finds that God is self-contained and there she stays abiding nowhere else.

41
00:04:17,362 --> 00:04:26,050
Augustine says: ‘As thou lovest so thou art: loving earth thou art earthly, loving God thou shalt be divine.’

42
00:04:26,050 --> 00:04:28,500
If I love God then, shall I be God?

43
00:04:28,500 --> 00:04:31,912
It is not I who say so; search the scriptures.

44
00:04:31,912 --> 00:04:36,950
In the Prophets God says: ‘Ye are gods and the children of the Most High.’

45
00:04:36,950 --> 00:04:40,662
I say that it is in his likes that God gives this birth.

46
00:04:40,662 --> 00:04:44,725
Had she no expectation of this the soul would not want to attain it.

47
00:04:44,725 --> 00:04:47,825
She wants to be preserved in him, he is her life.

48
00:04:47,825 --> 00:05:01,187
God has a preserve, a safe place in himself, which man can know nothing about until he pares off and is rid of all that belongs to the soul—her life, her powers, her nature, all must go.

49
00:05:01,187 --> 00:05:08,262
And that means standing in that perfect light where she and God are one form, where she finds herself God.

50
00:05:08,262 --> 00:05:14,525
It is characteristic of God to have nothing alien in him, nor on him nor added to him.

51
00:05:14,525 --> 00:05:21,412
And likewise it behoves the soul to have no outside impressions, nothing put on, nothing annexed.

52
00:05:21,412 --> 00:05:23,437
So much for the first (word).

53
00:05:23,437 --> 00:05:25,200
‘And behold’: ecce.

54
00:05:25,200 --> 00:05:31,325
This word ecce has all the meaning of logos (or word) and it could be given no greater.

55
00:05:31,325 --> 00:05:32,687
Word, i.e. God.

56
00:05:32,687 --> 00:05:35,487
God is a word, God’s Son is a word.

57
00:05:35,487 --> 00:05:43,462
It conveys the idea of our life and all our desire being centred in and dependent upon and oriented to God.

58
00:05:43,462 --> 00:05:48,362
As St Paul says, ‘By the grace of God I am’ that I am.’

59
00:05:48,362 --> 00:05:53,225
And again, ‘I live, yet not I but God liveth in me.’

60
00:05:53,225 --> 00:05:54,087
What more?

61
00:05:54,087 --> 00:05:55,175
Homo erat.

62
00:05:55,175 --> 00:05:57,312
He says, ‘Behold, a man.’

63
00:05:57,312 --> 00:06:04,275
We use the word homo for women as well as for men, but the Latins refused it to woman because of her weakness.

64
00:06:04,275 --> 00:06:07,300
Homo denotes something whole, nothing lacking.

65
00:06:07,300 --> 00:06:13,800
Homo, a man, a mortal, means one pertaining to earth, implying humility.

66
00:06:13,800 --> 00:06:23,362
Earth is the basest of the elements and placed in the midst with the heavens all round, it lies open to every celestial emanation.

67
00:06:23,362 --> 00:06:28,337
All the work and waste of heaven is caught midway in the sink of earth.

68
00:06:28,337 --> 00:06:40,062
Homo in yet another sense means moisture; as much as to say, one who is watered with grace; referring to those humble souls who receive the immediate influx of grace.

69
00:06:40,062 --> 00:06:50,062
In this inflowing grace there forthwith arises that light of the mind into which God is sending a ray of his unclouded splendour.

70
00:06:50,062 --> 00:06:57,125
In this powerful light a mortal is as far above his fellows as a live man is above his shadow on the wall.

71
00:06:57,125 --> 00:07:11,575
This light is vastly potent, not merely being in itself exempt from time and place, but anything it falls upon it robs of time and place and bodily semblance and everything extraneous thereto.

72
00:07:11,575 --> 00:07:18,175
As I have often said before, were there no time nor place nor aught beside it would be all one being.

73
00:07:18,175 --> 00:07:25,275
The man who is in this sense one and casts himself into the ground of humility, there will be watered with grace.

74
00:07:25,394 --> 00:07:30,231
Concerning the third point: this light deprives of time and place.

75
00:07:30,231 --> 00:07:31,344
‘There was a man.’

76
00:07:31,344 --> 00:07:32,719
Who gave him this light?

77
00:07:32,719 --> 00:07:33,781
The light did.

78
00:07:33,781 --> 00:07:36,831
This word erat belongs expressly to God.

79
00:07:36,831 --> 00:07:41,756
In the Latin tongue there is no word so proper to God as erat.

80
00:07:41,756 --> 00:07:46,769
John in his gospel comes to using erat as a synonym for pure being.

81
00:07:46,769 --> 00:07:54,819
Things are all extras: but addition is possible only in thought; not by mental addition but by mental abstraction.

82
00:07:54,819 --> 00:08:03,669
Goodness and truth are additions, in theory at least, but the abstract essence without anything to it is what is meant by erat.

83
00:08:03,669 --> 00:08:07,431
Again, erat implies birth, an end of becoming.

84
00:08:07,431 --> 00:08:17,056
I was coming to-day, now I have come; and if we eliminate time from my coming and having arrived, then coming and come close up into one.

85
00:08:17,056 --> 00:08:24,044
Where coming and come coincide, there we are born and re-made and re-formed into his primitive form.

86
00:08:24,044 --> 00:08:37,956
I have often said that all the while a thing’s aught is a matter of concrete existence it never will be re-created; refurbished it may be and coloured afresh, even as a seal that is old: that is restamped and renewed.

87
00:08:37,956 --> 00:08:48,081
A heathen doctor says, Things yonder no time can stale; there is the blessed life in the evermore: faultless, care-free, unalloyed being.

88
00:08:48,081 --> 00:08:54,844
Solomon says: ‘There is nothing new under the sun,’ though this is seldom taken in its proper sense.

89
00:08:54,844 --> 00:09:00,431
Everything under the sun grows old and dies, but yonder is nothing but new.

90
00:09:00,431 --> 00:09:04,106
Time brings two things: age and decay.

91
00:09:04,106 --> 00:09:06,631
What the sun shines on is present in time.

92
00:09:06,631 --> 00:09:16,231
Creatures are here and are from God, but yonder where they are in God they are not at all the same as they are here; they are as different as the sun is from the moon, far more so.

93
00:09:16,231 --> 00:09:23,206
Erat in eo, he says: ‘the Holy Ghost was in him,’ wherein is being and becoming.

94
00:09:23,206 --> 00:09:24,194
‘There was a man.’

95
00:09:24,194 --> 00:09:25,031
Where was he?

96
00:09:25,031 --> 00:09:26,219
In Jerusalem.

97
00:09:26,219 --> 00:09:33,169
Jerusalem meaning vision of peace; it stands, in short, for man’s peace and prosperity.

98
00:09:33,169 --> 00:09:35,369
It possibly signifies more.

99
00:09:35,369 --> 00:09:40,744
Paul says, ‘The peace that passeth all understanding keep your hearts and minds.’

100
00:09:40,744 --> 00:09:46,219
Pray God we may be such as to enter into this peace, which is himself.

101
00:09:46,219 --> 00:09:47,406
So help us God.

102
00:09:47,406 --> 00:09:48,281
Amen.
